 1601","1691":"1691","11 DEC 1599":"11. december 1599","Saint Andrew,Plymouth,Devon,England":"Plymouth St Andrew, Plymouth, Devon, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Tiverton, Cheshire, England":"Tiverton, Cheshire, England"},"nl":{"1576–":"1576–Overleden","1576–Female":"1576–Overleden","1575–Male":"1575–Overleden","1599–Female":"1599–Overleden","1601–Female":"1601–Overleden","1613–1691":"1613–1691","1555–1630":"1555–1630","1613":"1613","1601":"1601","1555":"1555","1599":"1599","1576":"1576","12 NOV 1595":"12 november 1595","1630":"1630","1575":"1575","02 DEC 1601":"2 december 1601","1691":"1691","11 DEC 1599":"11 december 1599","Saint Andrew,Plymouth,Devon,England":"Plymouth St Andrew, Plymouth, Devon, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Tiverton, Cheshire, England":"Tiverton, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1576–":"1576–Deceased","1576–Female":"1576–Deceased","1575–Male":"1575–Deceased","1599–Female":"1599–Deceased","1601–Female":"1601–Deceased","1613–1691":"1613–1691","1555–1630":"1555–1630","1613":"1613","1601":"1601","1555":"1555","1599":"1599","1576":"1576","12 NOV 1595":"12 November 1595","1630":"1630","1575":"1575","02 DEC 1601":"2 December 1601","1691":"1691","11 DEC 1599":"11 December 1599","Saint Andrew,Plymouth,Devon,England":"Plymouth St Andrew, Plymouth, Devon, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Tiverton, Cheshire, England":"Tiverton, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Burrowe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","variant of   Burrow  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>.","(mainly Sheffield): occasionally also a topographic name or occupational name for someone who lived or worked at a house with a chamber for conducting manorial business (Middle English <i>bour</i>, Old English <i>būr</i> ‘bower, chamber’, + <i>hous</i> ‘house’). Compare   Burroughs   and   Burris  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Burrowes","meanings":["English: variant of   Burrows  ."]},{"name":"Burros","meanings":["English (Surrey): variant of   Burrows  ."]},{"name":"Burrous","meanings":["English (Leicestershire): variant of   Burrows  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Burroughs","meanings":["English: variant of   Burrows  ."]},{"name":"Burrus","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Burrows  ."]},{"name":"Boroughs","meanings":["English: variant of   Burrows  ."]},{"name":"Burris","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire and Monmouthshire): variant of   Burrows  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Börries</b> or   Borries   or some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Burruss","meanings":["English: variant of   Burrows  ."]},{"name":"Burrow","meanings":["English:","topographic name for someone who lived by a castle or manor house, or in a town, especially a chartered town or borough (Middle English <i>burgh</i>, Old English <i>burg</i> ‘fortified place, borough, manor’), or a habitational name for someone who came from a place so named because it was a fortified town or near an ancient fort, such as Burrow (Leicestershire, Lancashire), Burrough Green (Cambridgeshire), Brough (numerous counties), and Peterborough (Northamptonshire); see also   Burgh  .","topographic name for someone who lived on a hill or near a mound (Middle English <i>bergh</i>, Old English <i>beorg</i>), or a habitational name for someone who came from a place so named, such as Burrow (Devon, Somerset). Middle English <i>bergh</i> became throughly confused with <i>burgh</i> in 1 above. Compare   Burrough  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Burrowe was born in 1576, in Tiverton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Tho Burrowe. She married James Newte on 12 November 1595, in Plymouth St Andrew, Plymouth, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1576–":"1576–Surnud","1576–Female":"1576–Surnud","1575–Male":"1575–Surnud","1599–Female":"1599–Surnud","1601–Female":"1601–Surnud","1613–1691":"1613–1691","1555–1630":"1555–1630","1613":"1613","1601":"1601","1555":"1555","1599":"1599","1576":"1576","12 NOV 1595":"12. november 1595","1630":"1630","1575":"1575","02 DEC 1601":"2. detsember 1601","1691":"1691","11 DEC 1599":"11. detsember 1599","Saint Andrew,Plymouth,Devon,England":"Plymouth St Andrew, Plymouth, Devon, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tiverton, Cheshire, England":"Tiverton, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1576–":"1576–Kuollut","1576–Female":"1576–Kuollut","1575–Male":"1575–Kuollut","1599–Female":"1599–Kuollut","1601–Female":"1601–Kuollut","1613–1691":"1613–1691","1555–1630":"1555–1630","1613":"1613","1601":"1601","1555":"1555","1599":"1599","1576":"1576","12 NOV 1595":"12. marraskuuta 1595","1630":"1630","1575":"1575","02 DEC 1601":"2. joulukuuta 1601","1691":"1691","11 DEC 1599":"11. joulukuuta 1599","Saint Andrew,Plymouth,Devon,England":"Plymouth St Andrew, Plymouth, Devon, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Tiverton, Cheshire, England":"Tiverton, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"1576–":"1576–Décédée","1576–Female":"1